  # Use the command line generator

      bundle exec builder generate <<your page slug>>

  You will be ask 2 things:

  - whether you want HAML template: answer 'no' if you're not familiar with [HAML](http://haml.info).
  - whether you want a localized template: answer 'no' (multilingual is another topic...)

  It will generate a file: `app/views/page/<<your page slug>>.liquid`.

  A page contains 2 parts: the header and the template itself.

  The header is enclosed by "---" and contains informations about the page using the yaml syntax.

      ---
      title: Page title
      published: true
      listed: false
      ---

  You already know about the template part. Remember it should start with your ["extends" liquid tag](/apidoc/tags/layout/extends) if you have one.

  Here are some possible options that can be used in the page header:

  <dl>
    <dt>title</dt>
    <dd>Pretty obvious... The page title is used in the backoffice and in your template if you use {% raw %}<code>{{ page.title }}</code>{% endraw %}. See more about the <a href="/apidoc/objects/page">page object</a></dd>

    <dt>published</dt>
    <dd>If set to false, the page won't be publicly visible once hosted in an engine. It will be visible with the builder server.</dd>

    <dt>listed</dt>
    <dd>The listed option is used to decide if the page should be listed in a menu.</dd>

    <dt>position</dt>
    <dd>Set the position among cibling pages.</dd>

    <dt>seo_title</dt>
    <dd>Set the title for SEO, you can use it through the <a href="/apidoc/tags/misc/seo">{% raw %}<code>{% seo %}</code>{% endraw %} tag</a> or {% raw %}<code>{{ page.seo_title }}</code>{% endraw %}.</dd>

    <dt>seo_description</dt>
    <dd>Same as seo_title for the meta description. You can use {% raw %}<code>{{ page.seo_description }}</code>{% endraw %} in your page template.</dd>

    <dt>seo_keywords</dt>
    <dd>Same as seo_description.</dd>
    
  </dl>


